01:15.413 --> 01:17.806
Vice has been covering
North Korea for years,

01:17.816 --> 01:20.575
and the country's relationship
with the United States

01:20.585 --> 01:22.343
has never been as unpredictable

01:22.353 --> 01:24.980
and as dangerous as it is right now.

01:24.990 --> 01:28.416
The North is testing evermore
sophisticated ballistic missiles

01:28.426 --> 01:31.919
that might soon be able
to reach American soil.

01:31.929 --> 01:35.223
And the US has threatened military
intervention if provoked.

01:35.233 --> 01:39.093
The Trump administration
is a new sheriff in town.

01:39.103 --> 01:41.929
North Korea is a problem.
The problem will be taken care of.

01:41.939 --> 01:45.200
As North Korea celebrated its
founder's birthday this year,

01:45.210 --> 01:47.768
Vice and a few other news organizations

01:47.778 --> 01:49.536
were invited to Pyongyang

01:49.546 --> 01:51.572
to witness a military display

01:51.582 --> 01:54.075
reminiscent of a
Stalinist May Day parade,

01:54.085 --> 01:56.777
a show of force that experts have warned

01:56.787 --> 01:59.321
could trigger a global nuclear war.

02:19.343 --> 02:22.468
We arrived in Pyongyang as
part of a press delegation

02:22.478 --> 02:24.503
invited by the government.

02:24.513 --> 02:27.140
We were told only that
we were about to witness

02:27.150 --> 02:30.944
a series of very
important announcements.

02:30.954 --> 02:34.114
Outside of here, the world's
talking about North Korea

02:34.124 --> 02:37.049
and what's going on here in big,
high-stakes terms.

02:37.059 --> 02:40.519
So I was expecting slightly
more of a tense vibe,

02:40.529 --> 02:42.963
but it's definitely
nowhere to be seen yet.

02:43.899 --> 02:46.559
No fancy missiles or marches yet.

02:52.475 --> 02:54.466
We've been told that
these thousands of people

02:54.476 --> 02:56.902
are all just regular Pyongyang citizens.

02:56.912 --> 02:59.571
What's most noticeable to me is

02:59.581 --> 03:02.440
the kind of palpable, subdued,

03:02.450 --> 03:05.752
quiet of everything.

03:18.333 --> 03:21.025
The eerie tranquility
stood in sharp contrast

03:21.035 --> 03:25.138
to the hysteria that was gripping
the news media everywhere else.

03:25.149 --> 03:26.741
Commercial satellite imagery

03:26.752 --> 03:30.201
shows activity at the test
site northeast of Pyongyang.

03:30.211 --> 03:31.769
Meanwhile, Reuters reported

03:31.779 --> 03:33.704
that foreign journalists
visiting North Korea

03:33.714 --> 03:35.873
have been told to prepare for a, quote,

03:35.883 --> 03:38.042
"big and important event" today.

03:38.052 --> 03:40.311
As North Korean citizens themselves

03:40.321 --> 03:43.146
were completely isolated
from these reports,

03:43.156 --> 03:45.382
we awaited a mysterious announcement

03:45.392 --> 03:47.992
from a very special surprise guest.

04:21.361 --> 04:23.820
In a perfect example of the disconnect

04:23.830 --> 04:26.689
between North Korea and
the rest of the world,

04:26.699 --> 04:29.158
this supposed nuclear announcement

04:29.168 --> 04:32.002
is actually the unveiling
of a new plaza.

04:47.486 --> 04:50.144
This would set the tone for our stay.

04:50.154 --> 04:53.482
Any visit here means,
at times, subjecting yourself

04:53.492 --> 04:55.149
to the same information bubble

04:55.159 --> 04:56.718
that North Koreans inhabit.

04:56.728 --> 04:59.087
We begin with new
concerns that North Korea

04:59.097 --> 05:01.723
could test-fire a nuclear
weapon any day now.

05:01.733 --> 05:04.192
Japan today claiming that North Korea

05:04.202 --> 05:06.527
may be capable of delivering missiles

05:06.537 --> 05:08.763
equipped with sarin nerve gas.

05:08.773 --> 05:11.366
And while we were out
here at a street opening,

05:11.376 --> 05:15.636
the US was sending a very
powerful message to Pyongyang.

05:15.646 --> 05:17.939
At around 7:00 p.m. local time

05:17.949 --> 05:19.941
in Afghanistan last night,

05:19.951 --> 05:21.376
the United States military

05:21.386 --> 05:24.978
used a GBU-43 weapon in Afghanistan.

05:24.988 --> 05:27.314
I wonder if maybe the
message on this MOAB

05:27.324 --> 05:30.017
was, "Happy birthday, North Korea."

05:30.027 --> 05:32.986
While the world news
talked of nuclear war,

05:32.996 --> 05:34.488
our government minders took us

05:34.498 --> 05:36.590
to something rather less threatening.

05:59.522 --> 06:01.581
This trip to the Children's Palace

06:01.591 --> 06:04.383
would be the first stop
on a sightseeing schedule

06:04.393 --> 06:07.587
which is the staple of
any visit to North Korea.

06:09.766 --> 06:11.924
A carefully curated PR tour

06:11.934 --> 06:15.261
designed to give an impression
of stability and prosperity

06:15.271 --> 06:17.338
in a place on the brink of war.

06:18.407 --> 06:20.866
While the outside media speculated about

06:20.876 --> 06:23.336
the supreme leader's march to war,

06:23.346 --> 06:24.937
the international news teams here

06:24.947 --> 06:28.173
were treated to an
elaborate musical recital

06:28.183 --> 06:30.809
with dancing penguins, dry ice,

06:30.819 --> 06:34.112
and a giant backdrop
of ballistic missiles.

07:04.986 --> 07:06.544
As other foreign guests

07:06.554 --> 07:08.813
danced with North Korean children,

07:08.823 --> 07:10.681
the message became clear:

07:10.691 --> 07:13.117
North Koreans are not only unaffected

07:13.127 --> 07:14.819
by these external threats,

07:14.829 --> 07:17.521
but wanted to show us that their society

07:17.531 --> 07:19.364
and military were thriving.

07:20.934 --> 07:22.993
At the Pyongyang Flower Festival,

07:23.003 --> 07:24.794
we would see a unique mix

07:24.804 --> 07:27.498
of nationalism and nuclear pride.

07:27.508 --> 07:30.800
This is an exhibition center of flowers.

07:30.810 --> 07:33.537
Namely, two types of flower,

07:33.547 --> 07:35.338
which are named after

07:35.348 --> 07:38.708
the founding father of
the DPRK and his son.

07:38.718 --> 07:42.378
They are called the Kimilsungia,

07:42.388 --> 07:44.321
and the Kimjongilia.

07:45.358 --> 07:47.417
What's the significance of the rocket?

07:47.745 --> 07:52.383
_

07:52.895 --> 07:54.498
Flowers and rockets.

07:54.509 --> 07:56.365
_

07:56.376 --> 07:57.437
_

07:57.448 --> 08:00.095
That one's a submarine-launched
ballistic missile.

08:00.106 --> 08:01.208
_

08:01.219 --> 08:03.074
Yeah, yeah.

08:04.723 --> 08:06.231
_

08:07.446 --> 08:09.038
While the outside world

08:09.048 --> 08:11.440
pondered the regime's next steps...

08:11.450 --> 08:12.875
While speculation has been growing

08:12.885 --> 08:16.278
that North Korea may be ready to
carry out its sixth nuclear test...

08:16.288 --> 08:19.582
... we were ushered through
a manufactured utopia

08:19.592 --> 08:22.417
which included a zoo,
natural history museum,

08:22.427 --> 08:25.954
and a high-end hair salon,
offering slight variations

08:25.964 --> 08:28.131
of one government-approved haircut.

08:29.701 --> 08:33.095
It's like a less-extreme version
of the supreme leader's.

08:33.105 --> 08:36.864
As families swam and we
sipped lattes at a bar,

08:36.874 --> 08:39.333
we had no idea what
was actually happening

08:39.344 --> 08:40.868
in the rest of the world.

08:40.878 --> 08:42.203
Or as we found out later,

08:42.212 --> 08:44.780
what might be about to happen here.

08:46.651 --> 08:49.110
We are sending an armada.

08:49.120 --> 08:52.047
A very powerful armada
is on its way to Korea.

08:52.058 --> 08:54.649
North Korea's getting ready
for another nuclear test,

08:54.659 --> 08:57.318
but it could really happen
any day now, right?

08:57.328 --> 09:00.154
In the event that nuclear
test does go ahead here,

09:00.164 --> 09:02.656
the speculation is that
the US would respond

09:02.666 --> 09:05.092
with some kind of tactical strike

09:05.102 --> 09:06.927
with the aim of knocking out

09:06.937 --> 09:09.363
some of North Korea's
nuclear capabilities,

09:09.373 --> 09:10.931
which potentially could lead

09:10.941 --> 09:13.066
to the most serious military escalation

09:13.076 --> 09:16.444
between the two nations,
in modern times.

09:17.480 --> 09:19.539
As talk mounted of the two countries

09:19.549 --> 09:21.274
potentially coming to blows,

09:21.284 --> 09:24.077
our minders took us to a metro station,

09:24.087 --> 09:26.379
which is where citizens
are instructed to go

09:26.389 --> 09:28.481
in the event of a nuclear attack.

09:28.491 --> 09:31.518
This is one of the deepest
metros in the world.

09:31.528 --> 09:34.554
It goes 150 meters underground,

09:34.564 --> 09:37.790
and apparently doubles
as a bomb shelter.

09:41.271 --> 09:43.229
This allowed us a rare chance

09:43.239 --> 09:45.431
to reach behind the iron curtain

09:45.441 --> 09:46.999
which surrounds North Korea,

09:47.009 --> 09:49.677
and communicate directly
with its citizens.

09:52.314 --> 09:55.141
Is this an exciting week in Pyongyang?

